The paper discusses a load adaptive multi-cell massive MIMO system that maximizes downlink energy efficiency. This involves modeling the load at each base station as an M/G/m/m state dependent queue, which falls under the category of information theory (cs.IT) and networked systems (cs.NI). The system also uses a game theoretic framework to determine the number of antennas to be used by each base station, which falls under the category of systems and control (cs.SY) and game theory (cs.GT). Finally, the paper discusses the potential energy savings of the load adaptive system, which could fall under the category of multimedia (cs.MM) if the focus is on reducing energy consumption in video streaming or other multimedia applications.
